# ================================================================================
D365 FINANCE & OPERATIONS: WAREHOUSE MANAGEMENT SYSTEM (WMS) DEEP-DIVE
Revision: January 2026
Author: Senior Solution Architect

---

## SECTION A: INITIAL CONFIGURATION (PARAMETERS & SETUP)

The foundation of WMS lies in the "Warehouse Management" module parameters and
the structural breakdown of the physical space.

1. CORE PARAMETERS:
* Path: Warehouse management > Setup > Warehouse management parameters.
* Key Settings:
* User location: Define the virtual location where users "hold" inventory
during movement.
* Staging/Shipping location types: Essential for defining the transition
points in the outbound flow.
* Work processing: Enable "Deferred work processing" for high-volume
warehouses to prevent UI locking during heavy transactions.




2. WAREHOUSE STRUCTURE:
* Enable WMS: On the 'Warehouses' form, the "Use warehouse management
processes" toggle must be set to 'Yes'.
* Location Profiles: Define the "DNA" of your bins (e.g., allow mixed items,
allow cycle counting, or use license plate tracking).
* Location Formats: Define the naming convention (Aisle-Rack-Shelf-Bin).
* Zone Groups & Zones: Logical groupings (e.g., Cold Storage, Dry Goods,
Bulk) used to drive location directives.


3. MOBILE DEVICE SETUP:
* Mobile Device Menu Items: Define the specific tasks (Picking, Receiving,
Inventory Lookup).
* Mobile Device Menus: Organize those tasks into a UI structure for the
handheld app.
* Work Users: Each physical worker needs a "Warehouse Worker" record
linked to their D365 user account.



---

## SECTION B: CORE BUSINESS LOGIC (STRUCTURES & RULES)

WMS logic is governed by the "Big Four" configuration elements:

1. WAVE TEMPLATES:
* Control the "Release to Warehouse" process.
* Defines if work should be created automatically or manually, and how
shipments are consolidated.
* 2026 Note: New 'Wave Parallelism' settings allow for faster processing of
waves containing thousands of lines.


2. WORK TEMPLATES:
* The "Instruction Manual" for a task.
* Defines the 'Pick' and 'Put' pairs. For example, a Sales Order template
might dictate: Pick from Floor -> Put to Stage; Pick from Stage -> Put
to Baydoor.


3. LOCATION DIRECTIVES:
* The "Brain" of the system.
* Tells the system *where* to pick from or *where* to put something based
on rules (e.g., FIFO, FEFO, or Empty Location with no incoming work).
* Directive Codes: Use these to bridge Work Templates and Location Directives.


4. WORK POOLS:
* Used to categorize work for different teams (e.g., Forklift Pool, Hand
Picking Pool).



---

## SECTION C: OPERATIONAL PROCESSES (DAILY & PERIODIC TRANSACTIONS)

1. INBOUND FLOW (PURCHASE/TRANSFER):
* Arrival: Mobile app 'Purchase Receive' -> generates 'Work'.
* Put-away: Mobile app 'Purchase Put-away' -> moves goods from receiving
dock to a storage bin determined by Location Directives.


2. OUTBOUND FLOW (SALES/TRANSFER):
* Release to Warehouse: Creates a Wave -> creates Shipment -> creates Work.
* Picking: Worker scans License Plate (LP) at the bin.
* Packing/Shipping: Optional manual packing station step or "Pick-and-Pack"
straight to the truck.


3. PERIODIC PROCESSES:
* Cycle Counting: Triggered by "Thresholds" (e.g., count when bin is empty)
or "Plans" (e.g., count Zone A every Monday).
* Replenishment: Minimum/Maximum triggers to move stock from Bulk to
Picking zones.


4. LEDGER INTEGRATION (GL):
* Sub-ledger Posting: Every WMS movement updates 'Inventory Transactions'.
* Posting Profiles: "Inventory Management > Setup > Posting > Posting"
controls which GL accounts hit during 'Physical' vs 'Financial'
updates.
* Item Model Groups: Must have "Post physical inventory" enabled to
track the value of goods currently in the "Picking" or "Staging" process.



---

## SECTION D: NEW 2026 FEATURES (AI & COPILOT ENHANCEMENTS)

The 2025 Wave 2 and early 2026 updates have transitioned WMS from reactive
to proactive management.

1. COPILOT INVENTORY INSIGHTS:
* Natural Language Queries: Managers can now ask, "Show me all shipments
delayed by backordered items in Zone B," without building a report.
* Anomaly Detection: AI identifies "Ghost Picks" (inventory the system says
is there but workers keep skipping) and automatically triggers a
Cycle Count.


2. AUTONOMOUS WAREHOUSE AGENTS:
* Copilot now acts as a "Virtual Dispatcher," automatically re-prioritizing
Work Items based on carrier arrival times and worker proximity to the bin.


3. SMART REPLENISHMENT PREDICTIONS:
* Instead of static Min/Max, AI analyzes seasonal trends to suggest
dynamic replenishment levels, preventing stockouts during flash sales.


4. MOBILE APP (VERSION 4.0) ENHANCEMENTS:
* AR-Assisted Scanning: Uses the device camera to highlight the specific
bin/item in Augmented Reality for faster onboarding of new staff.
* Multi-modal Input: Workers can use voice commands to confirm
quantities or report "Damaged Goods" hands-free.



# ================================================================================
END OF DOCUMENT

